    slug: "holnak-aag-qissa-syedna-ibrahim-silsila-qasas-ul-anbiya-630",
    description: `Holnak Aag (Qissa Syedna Ibrahim) Silsila Qasas ul Anbiya 6/30 is the sixth installment in the Urdu-language Silsila Qasas ul Anbiya (Series of the Stories of the Prophets), a thirty-volume collection that retells the stories of the prophets in narrative form for Urdu-speaking readers. This particular volume focuses on the dramatic episode of Prophet Ibrahim (Abraham), peace be upon him, being thrown into a massive fire by the tyrant Nimrud (Namrud) as punishment for Ibrahim's rejection of idol worship and his insistence on the oneness of Allah. The title "Holnak Aag" (The Great Fire) refers to this central event, one of the most famous and frequently referenced stories in the Quran.

The book narrates the full context leading up to the event of the fire, beginning with Ibrahim's intellectual and spiritual journey from his childhood in the household of an idol-maker — Azar — to his recognition of the falsehood of idol worship and his discovery of the true Creator through his observation of the stars, the moon, and the sun, as described in Surah Al-An'am. The confrontation between Ibrahim and his people is recounted in vivid detail, including Ibrahim's famous destruction of the idols in the temple, the trial that followed, and Ibrahim's challenge to his people to ask their idols who had broken them. The book then covers Nimrud's decree to burn Ibrahim alive, the gathering of enormous quantities of firewood, the use of catapults to hurl Ibrahim into the fire, and the Quranic account of Allah's command to the fire to become cool and safe for Ibrahim — "Ya naru kooni bardan wa salaman ala Ibrahim."

The narrative is written in accessible Urdu prose that brings the story to life for readers of all ages while remaining faithful to the Quranic account and the authentic hadith. The book includes the relevant Quranic verses and hadith references, allowing readers to connect the narrative to the primary sources of Islamic knowledge. The broader story of Ibrahim's life is also touched upon, including his migration, his relationship with his nephew Lut, his building of the Kaabah with his son Ismail, and the trials he faced throughout his prophetic mission. This volume is part of a systematic series that aims to familiarize Urdu-speaking Muslims with the lives and lessons of all the prophets mentioned in the Quran, making it suitable for family reading, Islamic school curricula, and individual study.`,
