    slug: "holnak-azab-qissa-syedna-shoaib-silsila-qasas-ul-anbiya-1430",
    description: `Holnak Azab (Qissa Syedna Shoaib) Silsila Qasas ul Anbiya 14/30 is the fourteenth volume in the Urdu-language Silsila Qasas ul Anbiya series, dedicated to the story of Prophet Shoaib (Jethro), peace be upon him, and the punishment (azab) that befell his people — the people of Madyan (Midian) and the people of the Thicket (Aykah) — for their persistent rejection of his message and their corrupt commercial practices. The title "Holnak Azab" (The Terrible Punishment) refers to the devastating divine punishment that destroyed the communities of Shoaib's people after they rejected repeated warnings, a story that is narrated in multiple surahs of the Quran including Surah Al-A'raf, Surah Hud, and Surah Ash-Shu'ara.

The book provides a comprehensive narrative of Prophet Shoaib's mission among the people of Madyan, a trading community located in the northwestern Arabian Peninsula (identified by many historians as the region near the Gulf of Aqabah). The Quranic account portrays the Madyanites as a people engaged in widespread corruption in their commercial dealings — specifically the practice of cheating in weights and measures, giving short measure when selling and demanding full measure when buying. The book explains how Prophet Shoaib addressed these moral and economic crimes directly, warning his people that their dishonesty in trade was a grave sin that would bring divine punishment, and urging them to deal justly and honestly in all their transactions. The related punishment of the people of the Aykah (the Thicket), described in Surah Ash-Shu'ara, is also covered, explaining the distinction between the two communities and the specific nature of each punishment — the earthquake that struck Madyan and the scorching heat that destroyed the people of the Thicket.

The narrative is rendered in clear and engaging Urdu prose, with references to the relevant Quranic verses and explanatory notes that help the reader understand the context and significance of each event. The book explores the moral and spiritual lessons embedded in Shoaib's story, including the Islamic emphasis on fair business practices, the consequences of economic exploitation, and the duty of prophets to speak truth to power even in the face of persecution. The story of Shoaib's daughter, who eventually married Prophet Musa (Moses) according to Islamic tradition, provides a connective thread to the broader narrative of prophetic history. This volume is designed to be accessible to readers of all ages and backgrounds, making it suitable for use in Islamic schools, family reading programs, and individual study.`,
