    slug: "holnak-toofan-qissa-syedna-nooh-silsila-qasas-ul-anbiya-330",
    description: `Holnak Toofan (Qissa Syedna Nooh) Silsila Qasas ul Anbiya 3/30 is the third volume in the Urdu-language Silsila Qasas ul Anbiya series, focusing on the story of Prophet Nooh (Noah), peace be upon him, and the Great Flood (Toofan-e-Nooh) that Allah sent to destroy the disbelievers of his time while saving Nooh and the believers aboard the Ark. The title "Holnak Toofan" (The Great Deluge) refers to the central event of this narrative — the catastrophic flood that is one of the most universally recognized stories in human religious tradition, narrated in the Quran primarily in Surah Nuh, Surah Hud, and Surah Al-Qamar.

The book provides a thorough and detailed account of Prophet Nooh's life and mission, beginning with the Quranic context that establishes Nooh as the first prophet sent to mankind after Adam, tasked with calling his people away from idol worship and towards the worship of Allah alone. The narrative covers Nooh's decades-long mission — spanning nine hundred and fifty years according to the Quran (Surah Al-Ankabut 29:14) — during which he patiently endured the mockery, rejection, and persecution of his people. The book details Nooh's various approaches to his dawah: his public and private calls to his people, his use of day and night as metaphors for the urgency of the message, his warning of the approaching punishment, and his unwavering patience despite the fact that only a small handful of people responded to his call.

The building of the Ark is narrated with particular attention to the Quranic details — how Allah inspired Nooh to construct the vessel, the mockery of his people who laughed at the sight of a man building a ship on dry land far from any water, and the significance of Nooh's prayer upon completing the Ark. The Flood itself is described with dramatic power: the opening of the heavens with rain, the bursting forth of the earth with springs, the boarding of the Ark by the believers along with pairs of animals, the drowning of Nooh's own son who refused to board, and Nooh's anguished prayer for his son — a powerful lesson about the limits of parental love in the face of divine will. The Ark's coming to rest on Mount Judi and the aftermath of the Flood are also covered. The Urdu prose is narrative and engaging while remaining grounded in the Quranic text, making this volume accessible to readers of all ages and suitable for use in educational and family settings.`,
